---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import LessonGrid from '../../../../../components/LessonGrid.astro';
import LessonPage from '../../../../../components/LessonPage.astro';
import LessonSection from '../../../../../components/LessonSection.astro';

const registration = `builder.Services.AddSingleton<AppInfo>();`;

const genericShape = `public static IServiceCollection AddSingleton<TService>(
    this IServiceCollection services)
    where TService : class
{
    // Simplified mental model, not exact framework source.
    services.Add(new ServiceDescriptor(
        serviceType: typeof(TService),
        implementationType: typeof(TService),
        lifetime: ServiceLifetime.Singleton));

    return services;
}`;

const normalCall = `orders.MapGet("/{id}", (int id) => Results.Ok(id));`;

const genericCall = `builder.Services.AddSingleton<AppInfo>();
// Same idea as calling a method with a value,
// except AppInfo is supplied as a type argument.`;

const laterResolution = `app.MapGet("/status", (AppInfo info) => new
{
    info.Service,
    Status = "ok"
});`;
---

<LessonPage
  title="Lesson 6 · Generic service registration"
  heading="Why AddSingleton<AppInfo>() does real work"
  lede="Today’s win: remove the magic from a generic DI registration."
  backHref="/topics/dotnet/"
  backLabel=".NET lessons"
>
  <LessonSection title="The confusing line">
    <Code code={registration} lang="csharp" />
    <p>
      Your question was the right one: this line does not look like it passes a real value. It seems to only name <code>AppInfo</code>. So where is the logic?
    </p>
    <Callout>
      Short answer: the logic is inside <code>AddSingleton&lt;TService&gt;()</code>. <code>AppInfo</code> fills the generic type slot, and the method uses that type to record a DI registration.
    </Callout>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="A generic type argument is still information">
    <p>
      In TypeScript, type information mostly disappears at runtime. In .NET, type information is much more present. C# code can ask for <code>typeof(AppInfo)</code>, and framework code can store that type as metadata.
    </p>
    <LessonGrid>
      <div>
        <h3>Normal method call</h3>
        <p>Pass a value: route string, number, object, delegate.</p>
        <Code code={normalCall} lang="csharp" />
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Generic method call</h3>
        <p>Supply a type: here, the service type to register.</p>
        <Code code={genericCall} lang="csharp" />
      </div>
    </LessonGrid>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Simplified shape of AddSingleton&lt;TService&gt;">
    <p>
      You do not need the exact ASP.NET Core source yet. The useful mental model is this:
    </p>
    <Code code={genericShape} lang="csharp" />
    <p>
      So <code>AddSingleton&lt;AppInfo&gt;()</code> means: “add a descriptor saying <code>AppInfo</code> is a service, create it as <code>AppInfo</code>, and keep one instance for the app lifetime.”
    </p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Important timing">
    <p>
      The registration line usually does not create the <code>AppInfo</code> object immediately. It records instructions. Later, when a handler asks for <code>AppInfo</code>, the DI container follows those instructions.
    </p>
    <Code code={laterResolution} lang="csharp" />
    <ol>
      <li>Startup: <code>AddSingleton&lt;AppInfo&gt;()</code> stores a registration.</li>
      <li><code>builder.Build()</code>: the app gets a service provider built from registrations.</li>
      <li>Request time: handler asks for <code>AppInfo info</code>.</li>
      <li>Container: creates or reuses the singleton <code>AppInfo</code> and passes it in.</li>
    </ol>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="One more lifetime nuance">
    <p>
      From yesterday: <code>Transient</code> is not “faster.” It often allocates more. Choose it when identity and shared state do not matter. A pure stateless helper can also be singleton if its dependencies are safe.
    </p>
  </LessonSection>

  <LessonSection title="Exercise — reply in Discord" variant="checkpoint">
    <p>Answer from memory, 3 short lines:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>In <code>AddSingleton&lt;AppInfo&gt;()</code>, where is the logic: in <code>AppInfo</code>, or in <code>AddSingleton</code>?</li>
      <li>What does <code>AppInfo</code> give the method?</li>
      <li>Does the registration line mainly create the object now, or store instructions for the container?</li>
    </ol>
  </LessonSection>
</LessonPage>
